<br>
Fumoto is now maxed at 210 skill with Innate First Aid 3 (let's him bind wounds to 100% health and is a prerequisite for Critical Mend).<br>
<br>
Each bandage heals one quarter of your skill, so max skill gets you 52 hp per bandage.<br>
<br>
Bind Wound skill refreshes in about two ticks, so when Fumoto stops and binds, it's like regenerating at about +26/tick or 260hp/minute.<br>
<br>
How much would some characters pay for an item with 26/tick regen? Lots. And yet many players ignore Bind Wounds skill.<br>
<br>
I specially like this skill with monks, because Bind Wounds in conjunction with Mend allows you to go from horribly mangled, to ready for action in ten minutes or less. And that's without any exterior healing.<br>
<br>
Some monks will likely come on here and &quot;pooh-pooh&quot; the skill with arguments like &quot;I have more HP than the sleeper, so even 26/tick isn't worth my effort&quot; or &quot;I never solo, and always have a healer around, so why bother&quot;.<br>
<br>
Here are some uses:<br>
-After a wipeout, bind casters to full health while the cleric meditates. This one can be a big timesaver. Naked, unbuffed int casters just don't have a lot of HP and can be returned to full health in a couple minutes after a resurrection, through the use of bandages.<br>
-If the cleric is out of mana, take care of small dings on the party.<br>
-If you happen to get a little damage here or there, take care of your own bruises between pulls, to preserve healer mana.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I'm babbling. Monks are fun.<br>
<br>
Fumoto Stonefist<br>
